"use strict";(self.webpackChunkcrypto_guide=self.webpackChunkcrypto_guide||[]).push([[398],{5357:function(e,t,n){n.r(t),n.d(t,{frontMatter:function(){return r},contentTitle:function(){return l},metadata:function(){return d},toc:function(){return u},default:function(){return h}});var o=n(7462),a=n(3366),s=(n(7294),n(3905)),i=["components"],r={title:"Innovating money"},l=void 0,d={unversionedId:"Chapter 1 : The basics/innovating_money",id:"Chapter 1 : The basics/innovating_money",isDocsHomePage:!1,title:"Innovating money",description:"People have needs & wants, and a lot of them, but we are unable to produce or",source:"@site/docs/Chapter 1 : The basics/innovating_money.md",sourceDirName:"Chapter 1 : The basics",slug:"/Chapter 1 : The basics/innovating_money",permalink:"/crypto_guide/docs/Chapter 1 : The basics/innovating_money",editUrl:"https://github.com/e5b47301/crypto_guide/docs/Chapter 1 : The basics/innovating_money.md",tags:[],version:"current",frontMatter:{title:"Innovating money"},sidebar:"tutorialSidebar",previous:{title:"ROADMAP",permalink:"/crypto_guide/docs/ROADMAP"}},u=[],c={toc:u};function h(e){var t=e.components,n=(0,a.Z)(e,i);return(0,s.kt)("wrapper",(0,o.Z)({},c,n,{components:t,mdxType:"MDXLayout"}),(0,s.kt)("p",null,"People have needs & wants, and a lot of them, but we are unable to produce or\nfulfill all of them by ourselves. However most people are able to produce one\ntype of product or provide one type of service, giving them the ability to trade\none product or service for another one."),(0,s.kt)("p",null,"The first type of trade ever made was bartering : trading a product/service for\nanother. For example if Bob has an apple & Alice has a banana, he can trade his\napple for a banana. It works well if Alice wants an apple, but if she wants a\npotatoe instead, she will not accept Bob's offer. For Bob to get Alice's banana,\nhe will need to find someone who has a potatoe & wants an apple, introducing\nmore people in the trade.\nBartering has a lot of problems : it's hard to find people to trade with,\nmatching product/services of equivalent value is hard, and the ability to trade\nis linked to the ability to produce a product & service. Apples only grow on\ntrees once a year..."),(0,s.kt)("p",null,"Instead of relying on direct trade between products & services, people gathered\nand agreed to use something as a medium of exchange : money. Money is an item or\nverifiable record that is generally accepted as payment for goods and services,\nand repayment of debts. The first examples of money were commodities, an\neconomically useful good whose units are interchangeable. For example, we can\nthink about bottles of water as a commodity money. Everybody needs to drink,\neverybody can accept water as a payment.\nHaving bottles of water as a medium of payment allows to trade any sort of goods\nand services. However, they have big problems : "),(0,s.kt)("ul",null,(0,s.kt)("li",{parentName:"ul"},"they are hard to store & transport (they take a lot of place & are heavy)"),(0,s.kt)("li",{parentName:"ul"},"water is abundant, it's value is low, and to be able to trade for\nsophisticated product, one would need a lot of them"),(0,s.kt)("li",{parentName:"ul"},"they are easy to steal")),(0,s.kt)("p",null,"One solution to some of these problems is to use a commodity that's more\nconvenient, like gold. Gold is a solid and can be turned into small tokens:\ncoins. Coins are small and light, easy to cary and trade. Gold is rare enough to\nfind and extract, so it's value is high, but it's common enough that it's\npossible to find more. Gold doesn't degrade over time."),(0,s.kt)("p",null,"Gold & precious metal don't have everyday usage, you can't eat it, or use it to\nheat your home, but people agree that it has value."),(0,s.kt)("p",null,'Today, most people use "fiat money" : like U.S. dollars (US$), euros (\u20ac), Indian\nrupee (\u20b9), Japanese yen (\xa5), pounds sterling (\xa3) ... Fiat money does not have\nany intrinsic value, and is usually made of a worthless or low-value material.\nThe value comes from a collective agreement, typically supported by a governement\nregulation that enforces its use & value.'),(0,s.kt)("p",null,"Gold coins are convenient, easy to trade & transport, but if you have a large\namount it's hard to safely store. Putting it under your bed is not safe and\ncould be easily stolen. Once stolen, a thief can use it to trade and it's almost\nimpossible to tell that it was stolen."),(0,s.kt)("p",null,"Instead of storing gold coins themselves, people trust banks to do it for them,\nusing vaults & armed security guards. Banks are now the one holding the\ncommodity. To let people keep trading, they deliver bank notes (cash, bills) to\nits costumers that they can use to trade. But Bank notes can be stolen & can be\ncounterfeited."),(0,s.kt)("p",null,"To try to prevent from thieves using bank notes that they stole, banks create\n\"cheques\". A paper form, that link the buyer, money sender to his/her bank\naccount. When Bob wants to buy Alice banana's, he can fill his cheque, with the\namount of money Alice wants, and sign it. Alice then needs to go to the bank,\nthe bank verifies the validity of the cheque, and transfers the money from Bob's\nbank account to Alice's bank account. However, cheques suffer from a lot of\nproblem :"),(0,s.kt)("ul",null,(0,s.kt)("li",{parentName:"ul"},"they can be tampered, Alice can decided to modify the amount written on the\ncheck"),(0,s.kt)("li",{parentName:"ul"},"they can be counterfeited, Marvin, can decide to create a fake cheque and\nimitate Bob's signature"),(0,s.kt)("li",{parentName:"ul"},"Bob can try to spend his money several times, money that he doesn't have. If\nBob's balance is 10 gold coins, and make 2 cheques of 10 coins, one of the cheques\nwill not be valid, and one person will not be paid. This is known as the\n\"double-spending problem\"")),(0,s.kt)("p",null,"Conscious of all these issues, banks introduced credit & debit card. Credit/Debit\ncard are easy to use & transports, they allow to make secure transactions from\none bank account to another, before making the transactions, banks will\nautomatically verify the balance of the buyer/sender. The buyer will not be able\nto double-spend.\nProblems of credit/debit cards :"),(0,s.kt)("ul",null,(0,s.kt)("li",{parentName:"ul"},"Need to share private informations, that can be stolen (cards numbers)"),(0,s.kt)("li",{parentName:"ul"},"Rely on 3rd party : banks, you need to trust the bank. There is no possible\ndirect trade between 2 people. Fees, 3rd parties & middlemen introduces fees to\nearn money. Banks usually have a lot of control on what you do, and can decide\nto decline a transaction or limit the amount you can spend."),(0,s.kt)("li",{parentName:"ul"},"Can be slow, some transactions will happened between different banks, using\ndifferent currencies, which can take several days to complete.")),(0,s.kt)("p",null,"What if you left blue land, to start living in dream land, you make money in\ndream land, and decide to send money to your family once in while. If a\ndiplomatic relationships degrade between the 2 countries, you will not be able\nto send money to your family anymore. Relying on governements & banks is a\nmistake."),(0,s.kt)("p",null,"Some countries are unstable, don't have governments, banks or even currencies.\nPeople living in these places don't have other choice but to rely on bartering,\nthey are the unbanked."),(0,s.kt)("p",null,"As you saw, creating a monetary system is extremely difficult, and all the\nprevious solutions have their problems."),(0,s.kt)("p",null,"Cryptocurrencies try to solve all of these problems."))}h.isMDXComponent=!0}}]);